.TH AIS 1 "June 2026" "ais 0.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ais \- associative index: store values under keys, retrieve them by keys
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.RB [ \-o ]
.IR KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B put
.I VALUE KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B put \-R
.I DIR KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B put \-
.I KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B find
.I TEXT
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.RB { add | del | del-key | dump | keys | stats | compact }
.RI [ ARG ...]
.br
.B ais init
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B import
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B doc
.I KEY ...
.br
.B ais
.RB [ \-f
.IR DIR ]
.B where
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ais
is a personal, plain-text associative index. A value (a URL, a path, or free
text) is filed under one or more keys; records are retrieved by the intersection
(default) or union of keys. With no command, the default action is
.BR get .
.PP
The store is append-only plain text and the index is navigable plain files, so
the whole index can be read, grepped, rsynced, and repaired by hand. Re-filing a
value already stored is idempotent.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-f " DIR"
Index directory. With no flag, the index is located by precedence: this flag,
then
.BR $AIS_INDEX ,
then the nearest
.I .ais/
at or above the current directory (like git), then the per-user index
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/ais
(else
.IR ~/.local/share/ais ),
created on first use.
.TP
.B \-o
For
.BR get ,
match ANY key (union) instead of ALL (intersection).
.TP
.B \-d
Debug tracing to standard error.
.TP
.B \-h
Short usage.
.B \-\-help
prints full help with examples.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the version and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.RB [ \-o "] " KEY ...
(default) Print records filed under all, or with
.BR \-o
any, of the keys, as
.IR id | value .
.TP
.B put \fIVALUE KEY ...\fR
File VALUE under one or more keys.
.TP
.B put \-R \fIDIR KEY ...\fR
File every file under DIR under the keys. Paths are stored relative to the
.I .ais
worktree root when there is one (so a moved tree still resolves), else absolute.
.TP
.B put \- \fIKEY ...\fR
File each line of standard input (one value per line) under the keys.
.TP
.B add \fIID VALUE\fR
Attach another value to record ID.
.TP
.B del \fIID\fR
Delete record ID.
.TP
.B del-key \fIKEY\fR
Delete every record filed under KEY.
.TP
.B dump
Print every record.
.TP
.B keys
List all keys, sorted and distinct.
.TP
.B stats
Print counts of records, keys, and deleted records.
.TP
.B compact
Reclaim space from deleted records.
.TP
.B find \fITEXT\fR
Print live records whose value contains TEXT (a plain substring), as
.IR id | value .
.TP
.B init
Create a local
.I .ais
index in the current directory (then found from any subdirectory, like git).
.TP
.B import
Read
.IR keys | value
lines from standard input and put each (the inverse of
.BR dump ;
blank lines and #-comments are skipped). Lines sharing keys recall together.
.TP
.B doc \fIKEY ...\fR
Save standard input as a document: write it to
.I <index>/blobs/<timestamp>.txt
and put that relative path as a value under the keys. For multi-line or large
text that cannot be a single-line value. Blobs are named by local time, so
.I ls blobs/
lists your documents in chronological order.
.TP
.B where
Print the resolved index directory (e.g. to locate a blob file).
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
ais put ~/photos/IMG_3920.jpg italy venice 2023
ais put -R ~/photos/venice italy venice 2023
find ~/photos -name '*.jpg' | ais put - italy venice 2023
ais italy venice
ais -o venice rome
ais find gelato
.fi
.SH FILES
These live inside the index directory (e.g.
.I .ais/
or
.IR ~/.local/share/ais ):
.TP
.I store
Append-only records,
.IR id | keys | value .
.TP
.I idx/<p>/<key>
Per-key posting lists (sorted record ids).
.TP
.I off
id->offset accelerator (rebuilt by compact; safe to delete).
.TP
.I multi
ids carrying more than one value line.
.TP
.I tomb
Tombstoned (deleted) ids.
.TP
.I blobs/<timestamp>.txt
Documents saved by
.B doc
(real data; not rebuildable).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B AIS_INDEX
Index directory used when
.B \-f
is not given (takes precedence over discovery).
.TP
.B XDG_DATA_HOME
Base for the per-user index
.RI ( $XDG_DATA_HOME /ais );
defaults to
.IR ~/.local/share .
.SH AUTHOR
Vasili Gavrilov.
.SH SEE ALSO
The project README, doc/dev/STYLE.md, doc/dev/LAYOUT.md.
